      "date": "2009-03-15",
      "explanation": "What's happened to our Sun?  It was sporting a spectacular -- but not very unusual -- solar prominence. A solar prominence is a cloud of solar gas held above the Sun's surface by the Sun's magnetic field.  In 2004, NASA's Sun-orbiting SOHO spacecraft imaged an impressively large prominence hovering over the surface, pictured above.  The Earth would easily fit under the hovering curtain of hot gas.  A quiescent prominence typically lasts about a month, and may erupt in a Coronal Mass Ejection (CME) expelling hot gas into the  Solar System.  Although somehow related to the Sun's changing magnetic field, the energy mechanism that creates and sustains a Solar prominence is still a topic of research.    digg_url = 'http://apod.nasa.gov/apod/ap090315.html'; digg_skin = 'compact';",
